238
00:16:17,560 --> 00:16:23,340
But if the chef was this blastoid system, they aren't looking at the soup.

239
00:16:23,340 --> 00:16:32,520
They're looking at the embedding space, the exact chemical recipe, the molecular structure, the exact gram weight of sodium and amino acids.

240
00:16:32,520 --> 00:16:33,960
I say, I like this soup.

241
00:16:34,200 --> 00:16:37,960
And the system maps that preference onto the chemical structure.

242
00:16:38,420 --> 00:16:44,420
And it uses that chemical map to decide what molecules to synthesize for my next course.

243
00:16:44,420 --> 00:16:46,580
That is a phenomenal analogy.

244
00:16:47,260 --> 00:16:49,040
You taste the emergent properties.

245
00:16:49,320 --> 00:16:51,660
The system manipulates the fundamental structure.

246
00:16:51,780 --> 00:16:53,720
And this fundamental structure is continuous.

247
00:16:54,320 --> 00:16:59,260
Which actually brings up a critical theory in the paper called the discrete to field interpretation.

248
00:16:59,640 --> 00:17:00,360
Let's dig into that.

249
00:17:00,420 --> 00:17:00,940
What does that mean?

250
00:17:01,400 --> 00:17:04,860
So we talked about the 5,000 images in the base corpus.

251
00:17:04,860 --> 00:17:09,620
Those 5,000 images are not the entire universe of retro wireframes.

252
00:17:09,760 --> 00:17:11,680
They are a finite, discrete sample.

253
00:17:12,120 --> 00:17:20,160
They are 5,000 specific points floating in that massive 512-dimensional continuous universe of meaning what the paper calls the manifold.

254
00:17:20,660 --> 00:17:21,460
Okay, the manifold.

255
00:17:21,860 --> 00:17:26,920
As you rate images, the system calculates your overall preference vector.

256
00:17:27,580 --> 00:17:29,180
They denote this as phi.

257
00:17:29,180 --> 00:17:36,020
Phi is essentially an arrow pointing in a specific direction within that 512-dimensional space.

258
00:17:36,540 --> 00:17:41,340
An arrow pointing toward the specific cluster of concepts, I seem to like.

259
00:17:42,200 --> 00:17:46,120
So if phi is an arrow, I kind of picture it like a flashlight.

260
00:17:46,380 --> 00:17:51,320
A flashlight shining into a dark, infinite universe of concepts.

261
00:17:51,700 --> 00:17:51,980
Yes.

262
00:17:51,980 --> 00:17:58,880
So out in the dark, there are infinite possible combinations of wireframes and glowing shapes.

263
00:17:59,180 --> 00:18:04,420
But right now, the system only has 5,000 actual rendered pictures.

264
00:18:05,540 --> 00:18:11,540
Those 5,000 images are just the objects that happen to be caught in the beam of your flashlight right now.

265
00:18:11,880 --> 00:18:12,480
Precisely.

266
00:18:12,880 --> 00:18:18,820
The system projects your preference, your flashlight beam, onto the discrete sample points available to it.

267
00:18:19,160 --> 00:18:22,720
And this highlights why using CLIP embeddings is so genius.

268
00:18:22,920 --> 00:18:23,500
Why is that?

269
00:18:23,500 --> 00:18:30,920
Because if the system used pseudo-random mathematical vectors or just raw pixel data, the space would be chaotic.

270
00:18:31,280 --> 00:18:33,060
The flashlight beam would mean nothing.

271
00:18:33,580 --> 00:18:37,540
Shining it to the left might suddenly give you completely unrelated noise.

272
00:18:37,540 --> 00:18:45,140
But because CLIP was trained by looking at millions of image text pairs from across human culture,

273
00:18:45,720 --> 00:18:52,420
the layout of that 512-dimensional space actually approximates human semantic understanding.

274
00:18:53,320 --> 00:18:58,220
Things that mean similar things to humans are physically clustered close together in the math.

275
00:18:58,680 --> 00:19:04,040
Your flashlight is illuminating concepts that make intuitive sense to a human brain.

276
00:19:04,040 --> 00:19:10,600
Okay, so the core goal for me, the operator sitting at the sonar screen, is to move this flashlight.

277
00:19:11,320 --> 00:19:13,460
To point it at the things I want to see.

278
00:19:13,600 --> 00:19:16,780
How do I actually power the engine of desire?

279
00:19:16,940 --> 00:19:19,120
Like, let's talk about the scoring mechanisms.

280
00:19:19,840 --> 00:19:26,140
The inputs I have as a user are shockingly simple for how complex the math is behind them.

281
00:19:26,180 --> 00:19:26,860
They really are.

282
00:19:26,860 --> 00:19:34,200
I am shown an image, I have three buttons, I can rate it awesome, which assigns a mathematical value of 1.0,

283
00:19:34,380 --> 00:19:42,180
I can rate it okay, which assigns a value of 0.4, or I can rate it horrible, which assigns a negative 1.0.

284
00:19:42,340 --> 00:19:46,860
And every single time you click one of those three buttons, the system immediately recalculates.

285
00:19:47,520 --> 00:19:53,980
It rebuilds your preference vector, phi, from scratch, taking into account your entire history of ratings.

286
00:19:53,980 --> 00:19:57,120
It updates the flashlight's position instantly.

287
00:19:57,600 --> 00:19:57,880
Yes.

288
00:19:58,500 --> 00:20:03,360
And once the flashlight moves, the system has to figure out what to show you next.

289
00:20:03,880 --> 00:20:11,600
To do that, it runs every single item in the active pool through a highly tuned six-part score function.

290
00:20:11,960 --> 00:20:16,260
This score function equation is basically the beating heart of the deep dive.

291
00:20:16,260 --> 00:20:25,540
The system is looking at every possible image and grading it across six different factors to see if it deserves to be on your screen.

292
00:20:25,840 --> 00:20:32,480
I really want to walk through these six factors because they reveal so much about what the algorithm values.

293
00:20:32,700 --> 00:20:33,400
Let's do it.

294
00:20:33,520 --> 00:20:35,060
First, there's alignment.

295
00:20:35,520 --> 00:20:43,520
This asks the core question, how closely does this image's mathematical vector align with your current preference field?

296
00:20:43,920 --> 00:20:46,000
Is it in the center of the flashlight beam?

297
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:46,300
Right.

298
00:20:46,740 --> 00:20:48,320
Second, there's explicit rating.

299
00:20:48,780 --> 00:20:50,480
This is a direct historical check.

300
00:20:51,180 --> 00:20:55,920
Have you, the user, directly rewarded this specific image in the past?

301
00:20:56,580 --> 00:20:57,760
Third, novelty.

302
00:20:58,620 --> 00:21:02,900
The system gives a mathematical bonus to images you have never seen before.

303
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:04,020
Very important factor.

304
00:21:04,480 --> 00:21:08,800
Fourth, repetition, which is the inverse of novelty.

305
00:21:08,800 --> 00:21:14,600
It applies a mathematical penalty if it has shown you the exact same image too many times recently.

306
00:21:15,440 --> 00:21:17,380
Fifth, offspring status.

307
00:21:17,860 --> 00:21:22,540
It gives a flat bonus just for being a newly created, genetically bred mutant.

308
00:21:23,020 --> 00:21:25,420
And finally, sixth, age decay.

309
00:21:26,020 --> 00:21:30,820
A penalty that grows over time for older creations that just haven't been rated.

310
00:21:30,820 --> 00:21:37,200
Now, before we discuss how the system weighs those six factors against each other, I want

311
00:21:37,200 --> 00:21:43,380
to circle back to the user inputs you mentioned, the 1.0, the 0.4, and the negative 1.0.

312
00:21:43,700 --> 00:21:46,440
Actually, yeah, I struggled with that when I was reading the paper.

313
00:21:46,640 --> 00:21:46,780
Yeah.

314
00:21:46,780 --> 00:21:48,900
Why is OK rated a 0.4?

315
00:21:49,300 --> 00:21:53,240
If I look at an image and think, eh, it's just OK, I don't love it, I don't hate it,

316
00:21:53,660 --> 00:21:55,980
shouldn't it mathematically be a flat zero?

317
00:21:56,400 --> 00:21:58,920
Why give it almost half a point of positive weight?

318
00:21:59,340 --> 00:22:04,780
It's a brilliant question, and it really cuts to the core of how algorithms interpret

319
00:22:04,780 --> 00:22:07,320
human indifference versus mild approval.

320
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:14,660
The authors explicitly state that an OK rating is set above zero because a positive, even a very

321
00:22:14,660 --> 00:22:18,760
weak positive rating carries vital directional information.

322
00:22:19,220 --> 00:22:20,900
What do you mean by directional information?

323
00:22:21,380 --> 00:22:23,840
Well, think about the physical act of rating.

324
00:22:24,360 --> 00:22:29,200
If you see an image and you find it completely irrelevant, you don't click anything, you ignore

325
00:22:29,200 --> 00:22:29,480
it.

326
00:22:29,600 --> 00:22:29,820
True.

327
00:22:30,100 --> 00:22:34,400
But if you take the time to click OK, it proves two things to the system.

328
00:22:35,320 --> 00:22:38,980
First, it proves you saw it and didn't immediately reject it.

329
00:22:39,480 --> 00:22:44,640
Second, it proves you found it at least acceptable within the context of your search.

330
00:22:44,660 --> 00:22:50,660
Even if it's not your favorite image ever, its vector is in a neighborhood you tolerate.

331
00:22:51,220 --> 00:22:51,740
Oh, I see.

332
00:22:52,200 --> 00:22:58,900
By assigning it at 0.4, it adds a tiny bit of gravitational weight to that specific direction

333
00:22:58,900 --> 00:23:01,160
in the 5 to 12 dimensional space.

334
00:23:01,600 --> 00:23:04,300
It gently pulls your flashlight toward it.

335
00:23:04,800 --> 00:23:11,600
If the system recorded a zero, it would mean your OK contributes absolutely nothing to the

336
00:23:11,600 --> 00:23:12,440
shape of the field.

337
00:23:12,440 --> 00:23:17,820
It would treat mild approval exactly the same as complete irrelevance.

338
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:18,420
Oh, wow.

339
00:23:18,520 --> 00:23:23,540
So even a lukewarm reaction tells the system, hey, there's a breathable atmosphere over here.

340
00:23:23,720 --> 00:23:26,100
Maybe explore this quadrant a little more.

341
00:23:26,360 --> 00:23:28,220
That is incredibly subtle.

342
00:23:28,380 --> 00:23:28,780
It is.

343
00:23:28,880 --> 00:23:29,120
All right.

344
00:23:29,200 --> 00:23:36,280
So the system recalculates my flashlight position and it grades every image using those six factors.

345
00:23:36,280 --> 00:23:42,460
Now, if this were a normal algorithm like YouTube or TikTok, if I show a strong preference for

346
00:23:42,460 --> 00:23:46,780
something, the system's immediate reaction is to hyper-optimize.

347
00:23:47,500 --> 00:23:49,420
It traps me in an echo chamber.

348
00:23:49,540 --> 00:23:49,840
Right.

349
00:23:49,940 --> 00:23:52,180
The classic recommendation loop.

350
00:23:52,340 --> 00:23:52,520
Yeah.

351
00:23:52,920 --> 00:23:58,800
If I watch three videos in a row about how to bake sourdough bread, the algorithm says,

352
00:23:59,260 --> 00:24:01,680
understood, you are now the sourdough person.

353
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:05,100
Here are 10,000 sourdough videos until the end of time.

354
00:24:05,100 --> 00:24:06,100
Exactly.

355
00:24:06,360 --> 00:24:12,100
But the paper emphasizes that blastoids pick breeder actively fights against this collapse.

356
00:24:12,720 --> 00:24:15,020
It has built in non-collapse mechanisms.

357
00:24:15,260 --> 00:24:15,540
Yes.

358
00:24:15,700 --> 00:24:17,960
And the philosophical difference here is profound.

359
00:24:18,540 --> 00:24:24,200
The objective of standard commercial recommendation algorithms is to minimize prediction error.

360
00:24:24,880 --> 00:24:30,180
Their singular goal is to find the one best item you are most likely to click on and just

361
00:24:30,180 --> 00:24:30,920
serve it to you.

362
00:24:31,040 --> 00:24:31,720
Keep you clicking.

363
00:24:31,720 --> 00:24:32,400
Exactly.

364
00:24:33,180 --> 00:24:36,880
But blastoids, mathematically, does not minimize anything.

365
00:24:37,420 --> 00:24:40,900
Its objective is to maintain a living, breathing distribution.

366
00:24:41,460 --> 00:24:47,740
It wants to show you what you like, yes, but it fundamentally refuses to let the entropy of

367
00:24:47,740 --> 00:24:48,980
the system drop to zero.

368
00:24:49,200 --> 00:24:51,460
Entropy meaning randomness, basically.

369
00:24:51,660 --> 00:24:51,960
Right.

370
00:24:51,960 --> 00:24:59,160
It refuses to collapse the universe into a single point of obsession, and it achieves this primarily

371
00:24:59,160 --> 00:25:02,020
through a mechanism called the temperature parameter.

372
00:25:02,260 --> 00:25:07,240
Let's unpack temperature, because that's another term that gets thrown around in AI circles a lot.

373
00:25:07,920 --> 00:25:13,760
In this system, temperature controls the randomness, the entropy of what you are shown next.

374
00:25:13,760 --> 00:25:18,340
The paper notes that when you first start a session, your temperature is very high.

375
00:25:18,540 --> 00:25:20,080
It's set at 1.55.

376
00:25:20,460 --> 00:25:20,780
Yes.

377
00:25:21,040 --> 00:25:24,420
Because it's high, the system is wildly guessing.

378
00:25:24,900 --> 00:25:30,800
It's showing you a massive broad sample of the base images to see what catches your eye.

379
00:25:31,560 --> 00:25:34,220
Then, as you start rating images, the temperature decays.

380
00:25:34,860 --> 00:25:35,840
It cools down.

381
00:25:36,300 --> 00:25:38,740
The system starts to focus in on your preferences.

382
00:25:38,740 --> 00:25:43,040
But here is the critical mathematical safeguard.

383
00:25:43,680 --> 00:25:45,580
The temperature decay stops at 0.42.

384
00:25:45,760 --> 00:25:46,720
It is a hard floor.

385
00:25:47,100 --> 00:25:49,180
It never, ever reaches zero.

386
00:25:49,440 --> 00:25:53,700
And to understand why that matters, we really have to look at what a temperature of zero would

387
00:25:53,700 --> 00:25:55,140
actually do to the system.

388
00:25:55,220 --> 00:25:55,980
What would happen?

389
00:25:56,140 --> 00:26:01,480
If the temperature hit zero, the algorithm would become deterministic and entirely greedy.

390
00:26:01,880 --> 00:26:06,100
Greedy meaning it just grabs the highest score and ignores everything else.

391
00:26:06,580 --> 00:26:07,100
Exactly.

392
00:26:07,100 --> 00:26:11,520
It would look at the score function, find the single image that perfectly aligns with your

393
00:26:11,520 --> 00:26:13,700
vector, and show it to you.

394
00:26:13,820 --> 00:26:16,220
And then the next time, it would show it to you again.

395
00:26:16,440 --> 00:26:16,940
And again.

396
00:26:17,200 --> 00:26:17,540
Forever.

397
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:20,920
Just a wall, the exact same sourdough video.

398
00:26:21,100 --> 00:26:21,420
Yes.

399
00:26:21,420 --> 00:26:28,500
By forcing the mathematical floor to stay at 0.42, the system guarantees that approximately

400
00:26:28,500 --> 00:26:33,880
15% more probability mass rests on non-top items.

401
00:26:34,240 --> 00:26:40,400
Even when the session is fully converged and it knows exactly what you like, the math literally

402
00:26:40,400 --> 00:26:46,600
forces the system to continually explore the fringes and edges of your preference field.

403
00:26:46,600 --> 00:26:52,160
So the anti-echo chamber is built into the physical laws of this digital universe.

404
00:26:52,300 --> 00:26:52,840
It is.

405
00:26:53,280 --> 00:26:57,880
And it combines that temperature floor with another mechanism the paper calls two-pool sampling.

406
00:26:58,420 --> 00:27:03,420
Every time the screen updates and needs to show you a new batch of images, it decides

407
00:27:03,420 --> 00:27:08,800
whether to draw an image from the original 5000 base corpus or an image from the offspring

408
00:27:08,800 --> 00:27:12,660
pool, the brand new mutants the system has been actively breeding.

409
00:27:12,660 --> 00:27:17,000
And the system enforces a strict unyielding ratio here.

410
00:27:17,180 --> 00:27:23,640
It always pulls exactly 22% of its images from the offspring pool and 78% from the base

411
00:27:23,640 --> 00:27:23,920
pool.

412
00:27:24,340 --> 00:27:28,460
Why do you think they enforce that specific structural constraint?

413
00:27:28,700 --> 00:27:31,280
Like what's the purpose of that 22%?

414
00:27:31,600 --> 00:27:35,680
Well, if I'm looking at this from the perspective of an echo chamber.

415
00:27:35,940 --> 00:27:36,220
Yeah.

416
00:27:36,220 --> 00:27:42,280
If there was no guaranteed ratio, the system would probably just default to showing me

417
00:27:42,280 --> 00:27:46,880
the base images I've already rated highly because they have proving high scores.

418
00:27:47,420 --> 00:27:47,520
Yeah.

419
00:27:47,740 --> 00:27:52,260
The newly bred offspring wouldn't stand a chance because they haven't been rated yet.

420
00:27:52,600 --> 00:27:53,920
They start with no history.

421
00:27:54,180 --> 00:27:54,840
Spot on.

422
00:27:55,120 --> 00:28:01,960
The 22% mixing ratio ensures that the visibility of these newly bred offspring is not determined

423
00:28:01,960 --> 00:28:03,900
solely by score dominance.

424
00:28:03,900 --> 00:28:05,480
Think about it.

425
00:28:05,580 --> 00:28:09,200
A newly generated mutant has zero explicit ratings.

426
00:28:09,960 --> 00:28:13,900
Its alignment might be a little weird because it's a genetic mashup.

427
00:28:14,320 --> 00:28:14,460
Right.

428
00:28:14,900 --> 00:28:20,200
If it had to compete fairly against your established favorites, it would never appear on the screen.

429
00:28:20,680 --> 00:28:26,440
The 22% guarantee means that regardless of score, a new offspring will appear in your

430
00:28:26,440 --> 00:28:29,760
stream at a stable rate of about one in five draws.

431
00:28:29,760 --> 00:28:35,920
The system absolutely guarantees that you will be exposed to weird, untested new experiments.

432
00:28:36,480 --> 00:28:41,860
Your preference field dictates which specific offspring are generated, but the mixing ratio

433
00:28:41,860 --> 00:28:43,260
guarantees that they are seen.

434
00:28:43,580 --> 00:28:44,660
That is so smart.

435
00:28:45,100 --> 00:28:50,100
I noticed another mathematical safeguard in the six-part scoring function we were talking

436
00:28:50,100 --> 00:28:50,940
about earlier, too.

437
00:28:51,600 --> 00:28:54,200
You remember the very first factor, alignment.

438
00:28:54,200 --> 00:28:58,020
How closely the image matches your flashlight beam.

439
00:28:59,020 --> 00:29:06,840
In the equation, alignment is weighted by a coefficient called alpha, and the authors set alpha to 0.55.

440
00:29:08,120 --> 00:29:13,700
If they had weighted alignment at a full 1.0, the system would instantly pigeonhole you.

441
00:29:14,420 --> 00:29:19,360
Alignment would be so mathematically heavy that it would completely crush all the other factors,

442
00:29:19,460 --> 00:29:21,860
like the novelty bonus or the offspring bonus.

443
00:29:21,860 --> 00:29:28,240
By deliberately capping the weight of things you already like, at roughly half its potential

444
00:29:28,240 --> 00:29:35,100
power, the system is forced to care about new things, unseen things, and newly bred things.

445
00:29:35,460 --> 00:29:38,620
It's a master class in balancing equations, really.

446
00:29:38,840 --> 00:29:44,260
It keeps the score function highly responsive to multiple sources of evidence, rather than letting

447
00:29:44,260 --> 00:29:46,280
historical preference become a tyrant.

448
00:29:46,840 --> 00:29:49,780
And this naturally leads us to the most exciting part of the paper.

449
00:29:49,780 --> 00:29:54,920
However, we've talked extensively about how the system scores and retrieves these newly bred

450
00:29:54,920 --> 00:29:58,740
things, but we haven't talked about how they are physically born.

451
00:29:59,240 --> 00:29:59,540
Right.

452
00:30:00,020 --> 00:30:01,580
We need to talk about the breeding layer.

453
00:30:02,660 --> 00:30:07,640
When the system decides it's time to play God and breed a new image, how does it actually

454
00:30:07,640 --> 00:30:08,160
do it?

455
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:13,880
According to the paper, the system looks at the top-ranked images in your current preference

456
00:30:13,880 --> 00:30:14,200
field.

457
00:30:14,200 --> 00:30:22,340
It selects two parent images, and it creates a child using one of three specific mutation

458
00:30:22,340 --> 00:30:26,020
operators, crop, color shift, and blend.

459
00:30:26,760 --> 00:30:28,420
Let's start by looking at crop.

460
00:30:28,760 --> 00:30:30,960
The crop operator is the simplest.

461
00:30:31,340 --> 00:30:35,040
It acts entirely within pixel space, what you see on the screen.

462
00:30:35,040 --> 00:30:41,400
It takes a single parent image, selects a soft-bounded region, let's say the top-right quadrant of

463
00:30:41,400 --> 00:30:49,980
complex wireframe, and rescales that specific quadrant to fill the entire 256 by 256 frame.

464
00:30:50,820 --> 00:30:53,180
Conceptually, it is a structural extraction.

465
00:30:53,580 --> 00:30:55,600
It zooms in on a specific detail.

466
00:30:55,860 --> 00:31:00,540
It's like finding a really cool neighborhood on a map of a city, and just drawing a box around

467
00:31:00,540 --> 00:31:01,760
it to make it its own map.

468
00:31:01,880 --> 00:31:02,320
Exactly.

469
00:31:02,320 --> 00:31:04,880
Then you have the second operator, color shift.

470
00:31:05,440 --> 00:31:06,780
How does color shift operate?

471
00:31:07,080 --> 00:31:08,680
Is it also just looking at the pixels?

472
00:31:09,400 --> 00:31:09,720
Yes.

473
00:31:09,960 --> 00:31:13,020
Color shift also acts entirely in pixel space.

474
00:31:13,580 --> 00:31:20,300
It applies a global screen mode tint overlay, either slightly warm or slightly cool, over a

475
00:31:20,300 --> 00:31:21,360
single parent image.

476
00:31:21,860 --> 00:31:27,800
The authors note that this is mathematically the weakest operator in terms of semantic impact.

477
00:31:28,060 --> 00:31:29,080
So it doesn't change much.

478
00:31:29,360 --> 00:31:29,620
Right.

479
00:31:29,720 --> 00:31:31,600
It introduces cosmetic variation.

